I think it's a
complicated problem.

00:02:45.530 --> 00:02:46.780
There are a lot of challenges.

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:48.654
But one I'd like to
bring up, because I think

00:02:48.654 --> 00:02:50.970
it's particularly
interesting to me,

00:02:50.970 --> 00:02:53.110
is what to do with the waste.

00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:56.700
And so one story that I
heard about actually there

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:59.050
was a documentary
made about this.

00:02:59.050 --> 00:03:05.340
Finland had this idea to create
this three-mile long tunnel,

00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:11.440
and they wanted to store 12,000
metric tons of nuclear waste.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:16.630
And they wanted the containers
to store it for 100,000 years.

00:03:16.630 --> 00:03:19.480
And this documentary asked
a number of questions

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:23.570
about this idea, such as, what
kind of container do you use,

00:03:23.570 --> 00:03:26.610
and how do you know the material
you design your container is

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:28.870
going to last 100,000 years?

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:30.440
As experimental
scientists, we like

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:32.380
to test how long things last.

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:35.980
But you can't really
do this experiment.

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:37.780
Also, it kind of
brought up the idea,

00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:41.560
do you guard this facility
for 100,000 years?

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:45.140
Because you can make bombs out
of a lot of this radioactive

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:45.690
waste.

00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:48.120
So you kind of
need to protect it.

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.080
But maybe you
should just bury it

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:51.860
